Moderate to heavy rainfall is likely to continue in different parts of the country as from April 14, the Meteorological Department has said. In a notice on Tuesday, Met said rains will be received in most counties including; Siaya, Kisumu, Homabay, Migori, Kisii, Nyamira, Trans Nzoia, Baringo, Uasin Gishu, Elgeyo-Marakwet, Nandi, Laikipia and Nakuru counties. Others are Narok, Kericho, Bomet, Kakamega, Vihiga, Bungoma, Busia, Nairobi, Nyandarua, Nyeri, Kirinyaga, Murang'a, Kiambu, Meru, Embu, Tharaka Nithi, Mombasa, Tana River, Kilifi, Lamu and Kwale. This will be accompanied by maximum temperatures exceeding 32°C in Mandera, Lodwar and Wajir counties. According to the forecast, there is a high risk of diarrhoea breakout especially in areas with poor drainage in different counties. "Residents are advised to look out for such diseases and take necessary action,"  Director of Kenya Meteorological Department Stella Aura said. The weather department has further advised Kenyans to look out for the daily forecast for more information. Last week, the department predicted that some parts of the country will receive heavy cumulative rainfall for this week. The weather forecast for April 7-13 indicated that Nairobi, Narok, Lamu, Taita Taveta, Kitui, Tharaka, Murang’a, Nyeri, Kirinyaga, Tana River, Garissa, Mombasa and Kwale counties will receive 70 mm rainfall. Nyamira, Bomet, Kisii, Kajiado, Nairobi, Machakos, Makueni, Meru, Kiambu, Embu and Kilifi counties were forecasted to receive moderate rainfall of between 20-70 mm. Light cumulative rainfall below 20 mm was expected over Mandera, Isiolo, Wajir, Bungoma, Siaya, Busia, and Laikipia counties.